# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: avgas
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] Strictly speaking, if the standard meaning of "iso" is followed, the name *isooctane* should be reserved for the isomer 2-methylheptane.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] However, 2,2,4-trimethylpentane is by far the most important isomer of octane and historically it has been assigned this name.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] Isooctane is produced on a massive scale in the petroleum industry by alkylation of isobutene with isobutane.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] This process is conducted in alkylation units in the presence of acid catalysts.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] It can also be produced from isobutylene by dimerization using an Amberlyst catalyst to produce a mixture of iso-octenes.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] Hydrogenation of this mixture produces 2,2,4-trimethylpentane.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] Engine knocking is an unwanted process that can occur during high compression ratios in internal combustion engines.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] During the 1920s different measurement methods of knock were proposed but laboratories struggled to reproduce them reliably.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] In 1926 Ethyl Corporation's Graham Edgar selected two specific hydrocarbons, *n*-heptane (commercially available in high purity from Jeffrey pine) and 2,2,4-trimethylpentane, itself first synthesized from tert-butyl alcohol via diisobutene by J.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] McKinney at the same laboratory in the same year, as primary standards.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] Compared to various chemicals and natural gasolines proposed before that, these two compounds had extremely close boiling points, ensuring the vapor mixture in the cylinder would be the same regardless of the carburetor, and didn't depend on the composition of particular crudes.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] This method became known as the octane rating scale.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] Test motors using 2,2,4-trimethylpentane gave a certain performance that was standardized as 100 octane.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] The same test motors, run in the same fashion, using heptane, gave a performance which was standardized as 0 octane.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] All other fuels were then graded against mixtures of these two chemicals and assigned octane numbers.
[src:avgas/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] In common with all hydrocarbons, 2,2,4-trimethylpentane is flammable.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:avgas/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] The **Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association** (**AOPA**) is a Frederick, Maryland-based American non-profit political organization that advocates for general aviation.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] AOPA's membership consists mainly of general aviation pilots in the United States.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] AOPA exists to serve the interests of its members as aircraft owners and pilots and to promote the economy, safety, utility, and popularity of flight in general aviation aircraft.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] With 384,915 members in 2012, AOPA is the largest aviation association in the world, although it had decreased in membership from 414,224 in 2010, a loss of 7% in two years.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] AOPA is affiliated with other similar organizations in other countries through membership in the International Council of Aircraft Owner and Pilot Associations (IAOPA).
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] In 2015, AOPA was inducted into the International Air & Space Hall of Fame at the San Diego Air & Space Museum.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] In September 2024, the AOPA appointed Darren Pleasance as its sixth President and CEO.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] Pleasance, with extensive experience in aviation and business, is set to officially assume the role on January 1, 2025.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] However, just over a year after taking on the role, Pleasance was removed by the board for unclear reasons.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] The organization started at Wings Field in Blue Bell, Pennsylvania.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] On 24 April 1932, The Philadelphia Aviation Country Club was founded at Wings Field.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] The country club was the location of meetings of members that founded AOPA.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] AOPA incorporated on May 15, 1939, with Charles Townsend Ludington serving as the first president.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] In 1971 the organization purchased *Airport World Magazine*, moving its operations to Bethesda, Maryland.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] On 1 October 2023, Senior Vice President of AOPA Air Safety Institute Richard McSpadden was killed in an aircraft accident near Lake Placid, New York.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] In November 2024 Mark Baker, the President and CEO of the AOPA, addressed concerns regarding the negative impact of increased customs fees on businesses in the Bahamas.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] These fees, which have been imposed on private aircraft flying into the region, have drawn criticism from the AOPA since the summer of 2024.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] Baker emphasized the potential risks to tourism and local economies, urging policymakers to reconsider the fees to prevent a decline in aviation-driven tourism and business activity in the Bahamas.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] AOPA sponsors its own Fly-In and open house in Frederick, Maryland.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] The yearly event started in 1991 with 125 aircraft.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] By 2001, the attendance grew to 760 aircraft.
[src:avgas/aircraft-owners-and-pilots-association] The event was cancelled for five years after the September 11, 2001 attacks and consequent airspace changes, but resumed in 2006.
[src:avgas/airventure] The airshow is arranged by the Experimental Aircraft Association (EAA), an international general aviation organization based in Oshkosh, and is the largest of its kind in the world.
[src:avgas/airventure] The show lasts a week, usually beginning on the Monday of the last full week in July.
[src:avgas/airventure] During the gathering, the airport's control tower, frequency 118.5, is the busiest in the world.
[src:avgas/airventure] EAA was founded in Hales Corners, Wisconsin in 1953 by aircraft designer and military aviator veteran Paul Poberezny, who originally started the organization in the basement of his home for builders and restorers of recreational aircraft.
[src:avgas/airventure] Although homebuilding is still a large part of the organization's activities, it has grown to include almost every aspect of recreational, commercial and military aviation, as well as aeronautics and astronautics.
[src:avgas/airventure] The first EAA fly-in was held in September 1953 at what is now Timmerman Field as a small part of the Milwaukee Air Pageant, fewer than 150 people registered as visitors the first year and only a handful of airplanes attended the event.
[src:avgas/airventure] In 1959, the EAA fly-in grew too large for the Air Pageant and moved to Rockford, Illinois.
[src:avgas/airventure] In 1970, when it outgrew its facilities at the Rockford airport (now Chicago Rockford International Airport), it moved to Oshkosh, Wisconsin.
[src:avgas/airventure] Much of the convention's growth and prominence on the world stage is credited to founder Paul Poberezny's son, aerobatic world champion and longtime EAA president Tom Poberezny, who became chairman of the event in 1977.
[src:avgas/airventure] For many years, its official name was *The EAA Annual Convention and Fly-In*.
[src:avgas/airventure] In 1998, the name was changed to *AirVenture Oshkosh*, but many regular attendees still call it as *The Oshkosh Airshow* or just *Oshkosh*.
[src:avgas/airventure] For many years, access to the flight line was restricted to EAA members.
[src:avgas/airventure] In 1997, the fee structure for the show was changed allowing all visitors access to the entire grounds.
[src:avgas/airventure] EAA AirVenture holds nearly 1,000 forums and workshops, in addition to their many vendors which bring a variety of aircraft supplies, general merchandise, and name brand sponsors such as Piper, Cessna, Cirrus, and many others.
[src:avgas/airventure] The 2020 AirVenture convention and air show was canceled due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:avgas/airventure] AirVenture has hosted the debut of numerous revolutionary designs.
[src:avgas/airventure] Van's Aircraft founder Richard VanGrunsven debuted his RV-3 at the 1972 AirVenture Oshkosh, a homebuilt that defined new ways of aircraft performance.
[src:avgas/airventure] VanGrunsven would eventually go on to build more homebuilts than anyone else in the world, exceeding the annual production of all commercial general aviation companies combined.
[src:avgas/airventure] In 1975, aircraft designer Burt Rutan introduced his VariEze canard aircraft at Oshkosh, pioneering the use of moldless glass-reinforced plastic construction in homebuilts, a technique that several aircraft went on to adopt in the ensuing years including composite airliners.
[src:avgas/airventure] Other past notable designs introduced at AirVenture include Frank Christensen's Christen Eagle II aerobatic kit biplane in 1978, Tom Hamilton's Glasair 1 in 1980, and Lance Neibauer's Lancair 200 in 1985.
[src:avgas/airventure] At the 2018 AirVenture, Jack Bally introduced his Bally Bomber B-17, a one-third scale, single seat homebuilt intended as a replica of the Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress, and Mike Patey introduced DRACO, a highly modified PZL-104 Wilga made for STOL and bush flying.
[src:avgas/airventure] The EAA estimated the attendance in 2021 at 608,000 people.
[src:avgas/airventure] In 2018, 2,714 international visitors registered from 87 nations.
[src:avgas/airventure] There were approximately 10,000 aircraft, 2,979 show planes, and 976 media representatives on-site from six continents, along with 867 commercial exhibitors.
[src:avgas/airventure] In the past, attendance at the event was tabulated on a daily basis rather than on an individual basis.
[src:avgas/airventure] It is unclear whether this practice still exists at EAA Airventure.
[src:avgas/airventure] For example, in 2006 the Oshkosh Northwestern reported that attendance was estimated at 625,000 by the EAA.
[src:avgas/airventure] The estimate was for total attendees each day, so one person attending 7 days would count as 7 attendees.
[src:avgas/airventure] The paper estimated that between 200,000 and 300,000 individuals attended the event.
[src:avgas/airventure] According to EAA CEO and Chairman Jack Pelton, attendance at the 2024 event was approximately 686,000.
[src:avgas/airventure] This was the highest in the organization's history, exceeding the previous record of 677,000 set in 2023.
[src:avgas/airventure] Pelton also said that more than 10,000 aircraft arrived for the 2024 event.
[src:avgas/airventure] EAA announced that attendance in 2025 was around 704,000.
[src:avgas/airventure] The large number of aircraft arrivals and departures during the fly-in week makes the Wittman Field FAA control tower the busiest in the world for that week in number of movements.
[src:avgas/airventure] To accommodate the huge flow of aircraft around the airport and the nearby airspace, a special NOTAM is published each year, choreographing the normal and emergency procedures to follow.
[src:avgas/airventure] More than 4,000 volunteers contribute approximately 250,000 hours before, during and after the event.
[src:avgas/airventure] The EAA AirVenture fly-in has a large economic impact on the Oshkosh area as well as the state of Wisconsin.
[src:avgas/airventure] In 1982, the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel reported that the fly-in had a large economic benefit to the Fox Valley region.
[src:avgas/airventure] At the time EAA estimated the benefit to be around $30 million ($100 million in 2024) and the Oshkosh Convention and Tourism bureau estimated it to be lower, at $21 million ($57.6 million in 2024).
[src:avgas/airventure] In 1989, the Oshkosh Chamber of Commerce said that Winnebago County had a $47 million benefit from the fly in.
[src:avgas/airventure] Additionally, a 1987 UW-Oshkosh study reported a $65 million ($184 million in 2024) benefit to the entire state of Wisconsin.
[src:avgas/airventure] In 2008, a UW-Oshkosh Center for Community Partnerships study showed a $110 million economic impact for the Oshkosh area.
[src:avgas/airventure] Of that, $84 million was direct impact with a $26 million multiplier from secondary spending.
[src:avgas/airventure] Additionally, the fly in provided 1,700 jobs and $39 million in labor income for Winnebago, Outagamie, and Fond du Lac counties.
[src:avgas/airventure] In 2017, it was estimated that the event had an over $170 million economic impact on the surrounding area.
[src:avgas/airventure] In 1961, the Rockford EAA airshow had 10,000 aircraft movements.
[src:avgas/airventure] In 1971, the EAA airshow at Oshkosh brought in 600 planes and 31,653 movements.
[src:avgas/airventure] Today AirVenture brings in more than 10,000 airplanes.
[src:avgas/airventure] Special air traffic procedures are used to ensure safe, coordinated operations.
[src:avgas/airventure] For example, in 2014 the special flight procedures NOTAM was 32 pages long.
[src:avgas/airventure] FAA air traffic staff, including controllers, supervisors, and managers, compete throughout the FAA's 17-state Central Terminal Service Area to work the event.
[src:avgas/airventure] In 2008, 172 air traffic professionals representing 56 facilities volunteered to staff the facilities at Oshkosh (OSH), Fond du Lac (FLD), and Fisk.
[src:avgas/airventure] They wear bright pink shirts to stand out in the crowd.
[src:avgas/airventure] Due to the budget sequestration in 2013, the Federal Aviation Administration announced that it was not able to send resources to support the AirVenture.
[src:avgas/airventure] Rather than cancelling the event, the Experimental Aircraft Association was forced to sign a $447,000 contract to repay the government for FAA resources during the AirVenture.
[src:avgas/airventure] EAA filed a petition in federal court arguing that the FAA could not withhold services without specific Congressional action.
[src:avgas/airventure] However, in March 2014 EAA signed a settlement agreement agreeing to pay the 2013 costs and a further agreement that guaranteed FAA participation for another nine years.
[src:avgas/airventure] The agreement required the association to reimburse the government for AirVenture specific costs that had been provided at government expense in the years prior to 2013.
[src:avgas/airventure] Several days prior to the event, members of the FAA's Technical Operation team from around the Central Service Area arrive in Oshkosh to set up the temporary communication facilities (mobile communication platforms, Fisk VFR approach control and Fond du Lac (FLD) tower).
[src:avgas/airventure] These technicians maintain the facilities during the event and tear down and store the equipment after AirVenture ends.
[src:avgas/airventure] EAA AirVenture relies heavily on volunteers who arrive in the weeks leading up to the air show.
[src:avgas/airventure] The tasks they perform range from parking cars and airplanes, to painting buildings, to helping set up and tear down concerts and shows presented by the EAA.
[src:avgas/airventure] Long-time volunteers receive free meals, tee-shirts, embroidered patches, and free admission into the EAA AirVenture event.
[src:avgas/airventure] National Blue Beret (NBB) is a National Cadet Special Activity in the Civil Air Patrol.
[src:avgas/airventure] The event is two weeks long and is set up so that the second week will overlap with the AirVenture airshow.
[src:avgas/airventure] Participants are Civil Air Patrol cadet and senior members who must go through a competitive selection process in order to attend the event.
[src:avgas/airventure] Participants help conduct event operations, including flight marshaling, crowd control, and emergency services.
[src:avgas/astm-international] In 1898, a group of scientists and engineers, led by chemist, industry leader, and proponent of standardization Charles Dudley, formed the American Society for Testing Material (ASTM) to address the frequent rail breaks affecting the fast-growing railroad industry.
[src:avgas/astm-international] The group developed a standard for the steel used to fabricate rails.
[src:avgas/astm-international] In 1961 the name "American Society for Testing and Materials" was adopted.
[src:avgas/astm-international] In 2001, ASTM officially changed its name to "ASTM International" and added the tagline "Standards Worldwide".
[src:avgas/astm-international] In 2014, the tagline changed to "Helping our World Work better." ASTM International had offices in Belgium, Canada, China, Peru, Washington, D.C., and West Conshohocken, PA.
[src:avgas/astm-international] In April 2016, the Safety Equipment Institute (SEI) became a subsidiary of ASTM International.
[src:avgas/astm-international] SEI is an accredited third-party certification organization that certifies various types of personal protective equipment to industry consensus standards.
[src:avgas/astm-international] On June 9, 2022, it was announced that the European Committee for Standardization (CEN) and ASTM International agreed to extend and expand a Technical Cooperation Agreement from 2019.
[src:avgas/astm-international] Membership in the organization is open to anyone interested in its activities.
[src:avgas/astm-international] Standards are developed within committees, and new committees are formed as needed, upon request of interested members.
[src:avgas/astm-international] Membership in most committees is voluntary and is initiated by the member's request, not by appointment or invitation.
[src:avgas/astm-international] Members are classified as users, producers, consumers, and "general interest".
[src:avgas/astm-international] The latter includes academics and consultants.
[src:avgas/astm-international] Users include industry users, who may be producers in the context of other technical commodities, and end-users such as consumers.
[src:avgas/astm-international] To meet the requirements of antitrust laws, producers must constitute less than 50% of every committee or subcommittee, and votes are limited to one per producer company.
[src:avgas/astm-international] Because of these restrictions, there can be a substantial waiting-list of producers seeking organizational memberships on the more popular committees.
[src:avgas/astm-international] Members can participate without a formal vote and their input will be fully considered.
[src:avgas/astm-international] As of 2015, ASTM has more than 30,000 members, including over 1,150 organizational members, from more than 140 countries.
[src:avgas/astm-international] The members serve on one or more of 140+ ASTM Technical Committees.
[src:avgas/astm-international] ASTM International has several awards for contributions to standards authorship, including the ASTM International Award of Merit (the organization's highest award) ASTM International is classified by the United States Internal Revenue Service as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.
[src:avgas/astm-international] In 2018, ASTM International launched the Additive Manufacturing Center of Excellence (AM CoE), a global initiative uniting industry, government, and academia to accelerate research, development, standardization, certification, and industrialization of additive manufacturing (AM).
[src:avgas/astm-international] Headquartered in Washington, D.C., with a network of experts across the Americas, Europe, and Asia, the AM CoE focuses on bridging the gap between cutting-edge research and consensus-based standards.
[src:avgas/astm-international] These initiatives aim to close standardization gaps, support qualification frameworks, and promote the broader adoption of additive manufacturing technologies across the aerospace, defense industry, medical devices, automotive industry, and energy sectors.
[src:avgas/astm-international] In 2021, ASTM International acquired Wohlers Associates, a consulting firm and market intelligence provider in additive manufacturing and 3D printing.
[src:avgas/astm-international] Wohlers Associates provides industry analysis and forecasts covering hardware, software, materials, and applications related to additive manufacturing.
[src:avgas/astm-international] Funded by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the Standardization Center of Excellence (SCOE) is a more recent initiative under ASTM International.
[src:avgas/astm-international] SCOE focuses on advancing innovation and standardization for critical and emerging technologies, offering a coordinated framework connecting R&D, standards development, workforce readiness, and regulatory alignment.
[src:avgas/astm-international] The SCOE enables cross-industry collaboration to ensure that next-generation technologies are developed, validated, and deployed with trusted, globally harmonized standards.
[src:avgas/astm-international] ASTM International has no role in requiring or enforcing compliance with its standards.
[src:avgas/astm-international] The standards may become mandatory when referenced by an external contract, corporation, regulation, law, or government.
[src:avgas/astm-international] In the United States, ASTM standards have been adopted by incorporation or reference in many federal, state, and municipal government regulations.
[src:avgas/astm-international] The 1995 National Technology Transfer and Advancement Act requires the Federal government to use privately developed consensus standards whenever possible.
[src:avgas/astm-international] The Act reflects what had long been recommended as best practice within the Federal government.
[src:avgas/astm-international] Other governments, including state and foreign, have also referenced ASTM standards.
[src:avgas/astm-international] Corporations doing international business may choose to reference an ASTM standard.
[src:avgas/astm-international] All toys sold in the United States must meet the safety requirements of ASTM F963, Standard Consumer Safety Specification for Toy Safety, as part of the Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act (CPSIA) of 2008.
[src:avgas/astm-international] The law makes the ASTM F963 standard a mandatory requirement for toys while the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) studies the standard's effectiveness and issues final consumer guidelines for toy safety.
[src:avgas/avgas] Kerosene-based jet fuel is formulated to suit the requirements of turbine engines which have no octane requirement and operate over a much wider flight envelope than piston engines.
[src:avgas/avgas] Kerosene is also used by most diesel piston engines developed for aviation use, such as those by SMA Engines, Austro Engine, and Thielert.
[src:avgas/avgas] The main petroleum component used in blending avgas is alkylate, which is a mixture of various isooctanes.
[src:avgas/avgas] All grades of avgas that meet CAN 2–3, 25-M82 have a density of 6.01 pounds per US gallon (720 g/L) at 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:avgas/avgas] (6 lb/U.S. gal is commonly used in America for weight and balance computation.) Density increases to 6.41 pounds per US gallon (768 g/L) at −40 °C (−40 °F), and decreases by about 0.1% per 1 °C (1.8 °F) increase in temperature.
[src:avgas/avgas] Avgas has an emission coefficient (or factor) of 18.355 pounds per US gallon (2.1994 kg/L) of CO2 or about 3.07 units of weight CO2 produced per unit weight of fuel used.
[src:avgas/avgas] Avgas is less volatile, with a Reid vapor pressure range of 5.5 to 7 psi, than automotive gasoline, with a range of 8 to 14 psi.
[src:avgas/avgas] A minimum limit ensures adequate volatility for engine starting.
[src:avgas/avgas] The upper limits are related to atmospheric pressure at sea level, 14.7 psi, for motor vehicles and ambient pressure at 22,000 ft, 6.25 psi, for aircraft.
[src:avgas/avgas] The lower avgas volatility reduces the chance of vapor lock in fuel lines at altitudes up to 22,000 ft.
[src:avgas/avgas] The high octane ratings were traditionally achieved by the addition of tetraethyllead, a highly toxic substance that was phased out of automotive use in most countries in the late 20th century.
[src:avgas/avgas] Historically, many post-WWII developed, low-powered 4- and 6-cylinder piston aircraft engines were designed to use leaded fuels; an unleaded replacement fuel is being developed and certified for these engines.
[src:avgas/avgas] Some reciprocating-engine aircraft still require leaded fuels, but some do not, and some can burn unleaded gasoline if a special oil additive is used.
[src:avgas/avgas] The annual US usage of avgas was 186 million US gallons (700,000 m3) in 2008, and was approximately 0.14% of the motor gasoline consumption.
[src:avgas/avgas] From 1983 through 2008, US usage of avgas declined consistently by approximately 7.5 million US gallons (28,000 m3) each year.
[src:avgas/avgas] As of 2024, the annual US usage of avgas was 180 million US gallons (680,000 m3), most of which contained lead, and 170,000 aircraft in the US used leaded avgas.
[src:avgas/avgas] In Europe, avgas remains the most common piston-engine fuel.
[src:avgas/avgas] High prices have encouraged efforts to convert to diesel engines burning jet fuel, which is more readily available, less expensive, and has advantages for aviation use.
[src:avgas/avgas] Grades of avgas are identified by two numbers associated with its Motor Octane Number (MON).
[src:avgas/avgas] The first number indicates the octane rating of the fuel tested to "aviation lean" standards, which is similar to the anti-knock index or "pump rating" given to automotive gasoline in the US.
[src:avgas/avgas] The second number indicates the octane rating of the fuel tested to the "aviation rich" standard, which tries to simulate a supercharged condition with a rich mixture, elevated temperatures, and a high manifold pressure.
[src:avgas/avgas] For example, **100/130** avgas has an octane rating of 100 at the lean settings usually used for cruising and 130 at the rich settings used for take-off and other full-power conditions.
[src:avgas/avgas] Antiknock agents such as tetraethyl lead (TEL) help to control detonation and provide lubrication.
[src:avgas/avgas] One gram of TEL contains 640.6 milligrams of lead.
[src:avgas/avgas] 100LL (pronounced "one hundred low lead") may contain a maximum of one-half the tetraethyllead allowed in 100/130 (green) avgas.
[src:avgas/avgas] Some of the lower-powered (100–150 horsepower or 75–112 kilowatts) aviation engines that were developed in the late 1990s are designed to run on unleaded fuel and on 100LL, an example being the Rotax 912.
[src:avgas/avgas] Automotive gasoline—known as mogas or autogas among aviators—that does not contain ethanol may be used in certified aircraft that have a Supplemental Type Certificate (STC) for automotive gasoline, as well as in experimental aircraft and ultralight aircraft.
[src:avgas/avgas] Some oxygenates other than ethanol are approved, but these STC's prohibit ethanol-laced gasolines.
[src:avgas/avgas] Ethanol-treated gasoline is susceptible to phase-separation which is very possible due to the altitude/temperature changes light airplanes undergo in ordinary flight.
[src:avgas/avgas] This ethanol-treated fuel can flood the fuel system with water which can cause in-flight engine failure.
[src:avgas/avgas] Additionally, the phase-separated fuel can leave remaining portions that do not meet octane requirements due to the loss of the ethanol in the water-absorption process.
[src:avgas/avgas] Further, the ethanol can attack materials in aircraft construction which pre-date "gasohol" fuels.
[src:avgas/avgas] Most of these applicable aircraft have low-compression engines which were originally certified to run on 80/87 avgas and require only "regular" 87 anti-knock index automotive gasoline.
[src:avgas/avgas] Examples include the popular Cessna 172 Skyhawk or Piper Cherokee with the 150 hp (110 kW) variant of the Lycoming O-320.
[src:avgas/avgas] Some aircraft engines were originally certified using a 91/96 avgas and have STC's available to run "premium" 91 anti-knock index (AKI) automotive gasoline.
[src:avgas/avgas] Examples include some Cherokees with the 160 hp (120 kW) Lycoming O-320 or 180 hp (130 kW) O-360, or the Cessna 152 with the O-235.
[src:avgas/avgas] The AKI rating of typical automotive fuel might not directly correspond to the 91/96 avgas used to certify engines, as motor vehicle pumps in the US use the so-called "(R + M)/2" averaged motor vehicle octane rating system as posted on gas station pumps.
[src:avgas/avgas] Sensitivity is roughly 8–10 points, meaning that a 91 AKI fuel might have a MON of as low as 86.
[src:avgas/avgas] The extensive testing process required to obtain an STC for the engine/airframe combination helps ensure that, for those eligible aircraft, 91 AKI fuel provides sufficient detonation margin under normal conditions.
[src:avgas/avgas] Automotive gasoline is not a fully viable replacement for avgas in many aircraft, because many high-performance and/or turbocharged airplane engines have been designed to use 100 octane fuel and modifications are necessary in order to use lower-octane fuel.
[src:avgas/avgas] Many general aviation aircraft engines were designed to run on 80/87 octane, roughly the standard (as unleaded fuel only, with the "{R+M}/2" 87 octane rating) for North American automobiles today.
[src:avgas/avgas] Direct conversions to run on automotive fuel are fairly common, by supplemental type certificate (STC).
[src:avgas/avgas] However, the alloys used in aviation engine construction are chosen for their durability and synergistic relationship with the protective features of lead, and engine wear in the valves is a potential problem on automotive gasoline conversions.
[src:avgas/avgas] Fortunately, significant history of engines converted to mogas has shown that very few engine problems are caused by automotive gasoline.
[src:avgas/avgas] A larger problem stems from the higher and wider range of allowable vapor pressures found in automotive gasoline; this can pose some risk to aviation users if fuel system design considerations are not taken into account.
[src:avgas/avgas] Automotive gasoline can vaporize in fuel lines, causing a vapor lock (a bubble in the line) or fuel pump cavitation, thereby starving the engine of fuel.
[src:avgas/avgas] This does not constitute an insurmountable obstacle, but merely requires examination of the fuel system, ensuring adequate shielding from high temperatures and maintaining sufficient pressure in the fuel lines.
[src:avgas/avgas] This is the main reason why both the specific engine model as well as the aircraft in which it is installed must be supplementally certified for the conversion.
[src:avgas/avgas] A good example of this is the Piper Cherokee with high-compression 160 or 180 hp (120 or 130 kW) engines.
[src:avgas/avgas] Only later versions of the airframe with different engine cowling and exhaust arrangements are applicable for the automotive fuel STC, and even then require fuel-system modifications.
[src:avgas/avgas] Vapor lock typically occurs in fuel systems where a mechanically-driven fuel pump mounted on the engine draws fuel from a tank mounted lower than the pump.
[src:avgas/avgas] The reduced pressure in the line can cause the more volatile components in automotive gasoline to flash into vapor, forming bubbles in the fuel line and interrupting fuel flow.
[src:avgas/avgas] If an electric boost pump is mounted in the fuel tank to push fuel toward the engine, as is common practice in fuel-injected automobiles, the fuel pressure in the lines is maintained above ambient pressure, preventing bubble formation.
[src:avgas/avgas] Likewise, if the fuel tank is mounted above the engine and fuel flows primarily due to gravity, as in a high-wing airplane, vapor lock cannot occur, using either aviation or automotive fuels.
[src:avgas/avgas] Fuel-injected engines in automobiles also usually have a "fuel return" line to send unused fuel back to the tank, which has the benefit of equalizing the fuel's temperature throughout the system, further reducing the chance of vapor lock developing.
[src:avgas/avgas] In addition to vapor locking potential, automotive gasoline does not have the same quality tracking as aviation gasoline.
[src:avgas/avgas] To help solve this problem, the specification for an aviation fuel known as 82UL was developed as essentially automotive gasoline with additional quality tracking and restrictions on permissible additives.
[src:avgas/avgas] This fuel is not currently in production and no refiners have committed to producing it.
[src:avgas/avgas] Rotax allows up to 10% ethanol (similar to E10 fuel for cars) in the fuel for Rotax 912 engines.
[src:avgas/avgas] Light sport aircraft that are specified by the manufacturer to tolerate alcohol in the fuel system can use up to 10% ethanol.
[src:avgas/avgas] Fuel dyes aid ground crew and pilots in identifying and distinguishing the fuel grades and most are specified by ASTM D910 or other standards.
[src:avgas/avgas] Dyes for the fuel are required in some countries.
[src:avgas/avgas] The 100LL phase-out has been called "one of modern GA's most pressing problems", because 70% of 100LL aviation fuel is used by the 30% of the aircraft in the general aviation fleet that cannot use any of the existing alternatives.
[src:avgas/avgas] The airframe must also be certified to use the fuel.
[src:avgas/avgas] In February 2008, Teledyne Continental Motors (TCM) announced that the company is very concerned about future availability of 100LL, and as a result, they would develop a line of diesel engines.
[src:avgas/avgas] In a February 2008 interview, TCM president Rhett Ross indicated belief that the aviation industry will be "forced out" of using 100LL in the near future, leaving automotive fuel and jet fuel as the only alternatives.
[src:avgas/avgas] In May 2010, TCM announced that they had licensed development of the SMA SR305 diesel engine.
[src:avgas/avgas] In November 2008, National Air Transportation Association's president Jim Coyne indicated that the environmental impact of aviation is expected to be a big issue over the next few years and will result in the phasing out of 100LL because of its lead content.
[src:avgas/avgas] By May 2012, the US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA Unleaded Avgas Transition rulemaking committee) had put together a plan in conjunction with industry to replace leaded avgas with an unleaded alternative within 11 years.
[src:avgas/avgas] Given the progress already made on 100SF and G100UL, the replacement time might be shorter than that 2023 estimate.
[src:avgas/avgas] Each candidate fuel must meet a checklist of 12 fuel specification parameters and 4 distribution and storage parameters.
[src:avgas/avgas] The FAA has requested a maximum of US$60M to fund the administration of the changeover.
[src:avgas/avgas] In July 2014, nine companies and consortiums submitted proposals to the *Piston Aviation Fuels Initiative* (PAFI) to assess fuels without tetraethyl lead.
[src:avgas/avgas] Phase one testing is performed at the William J.
[src:avgas/avgas] Hughes Technical Center for a FAA approved industry replacement by 2018.
[src:avgas/avgas] In July 2021, the first commercially-produced unleaded avgas, GAMI's G100UL, was approved by the Federal Aviation Administration through a Supplemental Type Certificate.
[src:avgas/avgas] Lycoming Engines provides a list of engines and fuels that are compatible with unleaded fuel.
[src:avgas/avgas] Prior to 2022, Teledyne Continental Motors (TCM) indicated that leaded avgas is required in their engines, and not unleaded auto fuels: "Current aircraft engines feature valve gear components which are designed for compatibility with the leaded ASTM D910 fuels.
[src:avgas/avgas] In such fuels, the lead acts as a lubricant, coating the contact areas between the valve, guide, and seat.
[src:avgas/avgas] They have announced a formal application to the FAA to approve the use of UL91 and UL94 in selected engines, stating that "Continental considers 91UL and 94UL fuel as a transitional step in a long-term strategy to reach a more sustainable aviation".
[src:avgas/avgas] Hjelmco Oil first introduced unleaded Avgas grades in Europe in 2003, after its success with 80UL.
[src:avgas/avgas] This grade of Avgas is manufactured to meet ASTM D7547.
[src:avgas/avgas] Many common Lycoming engines are certified to run on this particular grade of Avgas, and Cessna has approved the use of this fuel in a large number of their piston fleet.
[src:avgas/avgas] This fuel is also usable in any aircraft in Europe or the United Kingdom where the engine is certified to use it, whether or not the airframe is certified to do so, too.
[src:avgas/avgas] The firm Airworthy AutoGas tested an ethanol-free 93 anti-knock index (AKI) premium auto gas on a Lycoming O-360-A4M in 2013.
[src:avgas/avgas] The fuel is certified under Lycoming Service Instruction 1070 and ASTM D4814.
[src:avgas/avgas] Unleaded 94 Motor octane fuel (*UL94*) is essentially 100LL without the lead.
[src:avgas/avgas] In March 2009, Teledyne Continental Motors (TCM) announced they had tested a 94UL fuel that might be the best replacement for 100LL.
[src:avgas/avgas] This 94UL meets the avgas specification including vapor pressure but has not been completely tested for detonation qualities in all Continental engines or under all conditions.
[src:avgas/avgas] Flight testing has been conducted in an IO-550-B powering a Beechcraft Bonanza and ground testing in Continental O-200, 240, O-470, and O-520 engines.
[src:avgas/avgas] In May 2010, TCM indicated that despite industry skepticism, they are proceeding with 94UL and that certification was expected in mid-2013.
[src:avgas/avgas] In June 2010, Lycoming Engines indicated their opposition to 94UL.
[src:avgas/avgas] Company general manager Michael Kraft stated that aircraft owners do not realize how much performance would be lost with 94UL and characterized the decision to pursue 94UL as a mistake that could cost the aviation industry billions in lost business.
[src:avgas/avgas] Lycoming believes the industry should be pursuing 100UL instead.
[src:avgas/avgas] The Lycoming position is supported by aircraft type clubs representing owners of aircraft that would be unable to run on lower octane fuel.
[src:avgas/avgas] In June 2010, clubs such as the American Bonanza Society, the Malibu Mirage Owners and Pilots Association, and the Cirrus Owners and Pilots Association collectively formed the *Clean 100 Octane Coalition* to represent them on this issue and push for unleaded 100 octane avgas.
[src:avgas/avgas] In November 2015, UL94 was added as a secondary grade of unleaded aviation gasoline to ASTM D7547, which is the specification that governs UL91 unleaded avgas.
[src:avgas/avgas] UL94 meets all of the same specification property limits as 100LL with the exception of a lower motor octane number (94.0 minimum for UL94 vs.
[src:avgas/avgas] 99.6 minimum for 100LL) and a decreased maximum lead content.
[src:avgas/avgas] UL94 is an unleaded fuel, but as with all ASTM International unleaded gasoline specifications, a *de minimis* amount of unintentionally added lead is permitted.
[src:avgas/avgas] Since May 2016, UL94, now a product of Swift Fuels, is available for sale at dozens of airports in the United States.
[src:avgas/avgas] Swift Fuels has an agreement for distribution in Europe.
[src:avgas/avgas] UL94 is not intended to be a full replacement for 100LL, but rather is designed to be a drop-in replacement for aircraft with lower-octane-rated engines, such as those that are approved for operation on Grade 80 avgas (or lower), UL91, or mogas.
[src:avgas/avgas] It is estimated that up to 65% of the fleet of current general aviation piston-engine-powered aircraft can operate on UL94 with no modifications to either the engine or airframe.
[src:avgas/avgas] Some aircraft, however, do require a FAA-approved Supplemental Type Certificate (STC) to be purchased to allow for operation on UL94.
[src:avgas/avgas] UL94 has a minimum Motor octane number (MON, which is the octane rating employed for grading aviation gasoline) of 94.0.
[src:avgas/avgas] AKI is the octane rating used to grade all U.S. automotive gasoline (typical values at the pump can include 87, 89, 91, and 93), and also the 93UL fuel from Airworthy AutoGas.
[src:avgas/avgas] The minimum AKI of UL94, as sold by Swift Fuels, is 98.0.
[src:avgas/avgas] The publication of the SAIB, especially the August 2016 revision, eliminated the need for many of the UL94 STCs being sold by Swift Fuels, as the majority of the aircraft on the STC's Approved Model List are type-certified to use 80-octane or lower avgas.
[src:avgas/avgas] On April 6, 2017, Lycoming Engines published Service Instruction 1070V, which adds UL94 as an approved grade of fuel for dozens of engine models, 60% of which are carbureted engines.
[src:avgas/avgas] Engines with displacements of 235, 320, 360, and 540 cubic inches make up almost 90% of the models approved for UL94.
[src:avgas/avgas] Swift Fuels, LLC, has attained approval to produce fuel for testing at its pilot plant in Indiana.
[src:avgas/avgas] Composed of approximately 85% mesitylene and 15% isopentane, the fuel is reportedly scheduled for extensive testing by the FAA to receive certification under the new ASTM D7719 guideline for unleaded 100LL replacement fuels.
[src:avgas/avgas] The company eventually intends to produce the fuel from renewable biomass feedstocks, and aims to produce something competitive in price with 100LL and currently available alternative fuels.
[src:avgas/avgas] Swift Fuels has suggested that the fuel, formerly referred to as 100SF, will be available for "high performance piston-powered aircraft" before 2020.
[src:avgas/avgas] John and Mary-Louise Rusek founded Swift Enterprises in 2001 to develop renewable fuels and hydrogen fuel cells.
[src:avgas/avgas] They began testing "Swift 142" in 2006 and patented several alternatives for non-alcohol based fuels which can be derived from biomass fermentation.
[src:avgas/avgas] Over the next several years, the company sought to build a pilot plant to produce enough fuel for larger-scale testing and submitted fuel to the FAA for testing.
[src:avgas/avgas] In 2008, an article by technology writer and aviation enthusiast Robert X.
[src:avgas/avgas] Cringely attracted popular attention to the fuel, as also did a cross-country Swift-Fueled flight by the AOPA's Dave Hirschman.
[src:avgas/avgas] Swift Enterprises' claims that the fuel could eventually be manufactured much more cheaply than 100LL have been debated in the aviation press.
[src:avgas/avgas] The FAA found Swift Fuel to have a motor octane number of 104.4, 96.3% of the energy per unit of mass, and 113% of the energy per unit of volume as 100LL, and to meet most of the ASTM D910 standard for leaded aviation fuel.
[src:avgas/avgas] Following tests in two Lycoming engines, the FAA concluded it performs better than 100LL in detonation testing and will provide a fuel saving of 8% per unit of volume, though it weighs 1 pound per US gallon (120 g/L) more than 100LL.
[src:avgas/avgas] GC–FID testing showed the fuel to be made primarily of two components — one about 85% by weight and the other about 14% by weight.
[src:avgas/avgas] Soon afterward, AVweb reported that Continental had begun the process of certifying several of its engines to use the new fuel.
[src:avgas/avgas] In 2012, Swift Fuels LLC was formed to bring in oil and gas industry experience, scale up production and bring the fuel to market.
[src:avgas/avgas] By November 2013, the company had built its pilot plant and received approval to produce fuel in it.
[src:avgas/avgas] Its most recent patent, approved in 2013, describes methods by which the fuel can be produced from fermentable biomass.
[src:avgas/avgas] The FAA scheduled UL102 for 2 years of phase 2 testing in its PAFI initiative beginning in the summer of 2016.
[src:avgas/avgas] In February 2010, General Aviation Modifications Inc.
[src:avgas/avgas] (GAMI) announced that it was in the process of developing a 100LL replacement to be called G100UL ("unleaded").
[src:avgas/avgas] This fuel is made by blending existing refinery products and yields detonation margins comparable to 100LL.
[src:avgas/avgas] The new fuel is slightly more dense than 100LL, but has a 3.5% higher thermodynamic output.
[src:avgas/avgas] G100UL is compatible with 100LL and can be mixed with it in aircraft tanks for use.
[src:avgas/avgas] In demonstrations held in July 2010, G100UL performed better than 100LL that just meets the minimum specification and performed as well as average production 100LL.
[src:avgas/avgas] G100UL was approved by the Federal Aviation Administration by the issuance of a Supplemental Type Certificate at AirVenture in July 2021.
[src:avgas/avgas] The STC was initially only applicable to Lycoming-powered models of the Cessna 172.
[src:avgas/avgas] The company indicated that the retail cost was expected to be 0.60–0.85 US dollars per US gallon higher than 100LL.
[src:avgas/avgas] This was later revised to 1.00 US dollar per US gallon.
[src:avgas/avgas] In 2022, Paul Bertorelli of AVweb reported that the FAA was dragging its feet on broadly certifying G100UL, delaying approval of the fuel for more engines and spending over $80 million on EAGLE to re-start a search for an unleaded fuel when G100UL had been under evaluation for over 10 years.
[src:avgas/avgas] In September 2022, in a surprise announcement, the FAA approved an STC for the use of the fuel for all piston-engined aircraft and engine combinations.
[src:avgas/avgas] In February 2023, GAMI began selling supplemental type certificates to allow aircraft owners to use the fuel when it becomes available.
[src:avgas/avgas] In April 2024, GAMI announced that 1 million gallons of G100UL had been produced.
[src:avgas/avgas] Fuel availability in the US was forecast for airports in California, Washington and Oregon by the middle of 2024 and the rest of the country by 2026.
[src:avgas/avgas] In December 2024, shortly after G100UL was made available at selected airports in California, several concerns regarding material compatibility arose, as users reported fuel leaks, paint staining, and paint stripping.
[src:avgas/avgas] In December 2013, Shell Oil announced that they had developed an unleaded 100 octane fuel and will submit it for FAA testing with certification expected within two to three years.
[src:avgas/avgas] The fuel is alkylate-based with an additive package of aromatics.
[src:avgas/avgas] No information has yet been published with regard to its performance, producibility or price.
[src:avgas/avgas] Industry analysts have indicated that it will likely cost as much as or more than existing 100LL.
[src:avgas/avgas] In 2018, LyondellBasell and VP Racing Fuels, an established motorsport fuel manufacturer, announced its intention to participate in developing an unleaded fuel for piston-powered aircraft.
[src:avgas/avgas] As of December 2024, it has reached Phase 4 of testing, according to the FAA.
[src:avgas/avgas] TEL found in leaded avgas and its combustion products are potent neurotoxins that have been shown in scientific research to interfere with brain development in children.
[src:avgas/avgas] Children in residences or childcare facilities in close proximity to airports with moderate to high piston engine aircraft traffic are at especially high risk of high blood lead levels.
[src:avgas/avgas] On November 16, 2007, the environmental group Friends of the Earth formally petitioned the EPA, asking them to regulate leaded avgas.
[src:avgas/avgas] The EPA responded with a notice of petition for rulemaking.
[src:avgas/avgas] The public comment period on this petition closed on March 17, 2008.
[src:avgas/avgas] Under a federal court order to set a new standard by October 15, 2008, the EPA cut the acceptable limits for atmospheric lead from the previous standard of 1.5 μg/m3 to 0.15 μg/m3.
[src:avgas/avgas] This was the first change to the standard since 1978 and represents an order of magnitude reduction over previous levels.
[src:avgas/avgas] The EPA's own studies have shown that to prevent a measurable decrease in IQ for children deemed most vulnerable, the standard needs to be set much lower, to 0.02 μg/m3.
[src:avgas/avgas] The EPA identified avgas as one of the most "significant sources of lead".
[src:avgas/avgas] In December 2008, AOPA filed formal comments to the new EPA regulations.
[src:avgas/avgas] AOPA has asked the EPA to account for the cost and the safety issues involved with removing lead from avgas.
[src:avgas/avgas] They cited that the aviation sector employs more than 1.3 million people in the US and has an economic direct and indirect effect that "exceeds $150 billion annually".
[src:avgas/avgas] AOPA interprets the new regulations as not affecting general aviation as they are currently written.
[src:avgas/avgas] Publication in the USA Federal Register of an Advance Notice of Proposed Rulemaking by the USA EPA occurred in April 2010.
[src:avgas/avgas] Despite assertions in the media that leaded avgas will be eliminated in the US by 2017 at the latest date, the EPA confirmed in July 2010 that there is no phase-out date and that setting one would be an FAA responsibility as the EPA has no authority over avgas.
[src:avgas/avgas] The FAA administrator stated that regulating lead in avgas is an EPA responsibility, resulting in widespread criticism of both organizations for causing confusion and delaying solutions.
[src:avgas/avgas] "There is no reason to believe 100 low-lead will become unavailable in the foreseeable future," Fuller stated.
[src:avgas/avgas] Final results from EPA's lead modeling study at the Santa Monica Airport shows off-airport levels below current 150 ng/m3 and possible future 20 ng/m3 levels.
[src:avgas/avgas] Fifteen of 17 airports monitored during a year-long study in the US by the EPA have lead emissions well below the current National Ambient Air Quality Standard (NAAQS) for lead.
[src:avgas/avgas] Avgas is occasionally used in amateur auto racing cars as its octane rating is higher than automotive gasoline thus allowing the engines to run at higher compression ratios.
